706,IssuesEvent,2015-06-04 18:36:33+00:00,17250474,szaghi/FoBiS,1668392,sanguinariojoe,,,opened,Useless __initialized__ stuff,[],[],0,"It is a little bit strange how FoBiS is initialized, resulting in an unnecessary obfuscation...

In fobis.py:7, you are importing the configuration module (which is actually FoBiS itself, or at least the main engine) with a strange command:
    from .config import __config__
It is used just when you are trying to generate a private subclass, but I can't see the point here. Anyway... This command is executing the code in config.py:642:
    # global variables
    __initialized__ = False
    if not __initialized__:
      __config__ = FoBiSConfig()
      __initialized__ = True
Which, as far as I can see, is trying to avoid calling FoBiSConfig creation more than once. I should mention right here that just __init__() has been defined in the class, no __new__(). Then program is coming back to fobis.py:14:
    __config__.run_fobis()
In the very first line of the function the following is executed (config.py:612):
    self._reset()
Which are just calling:
    self.__init__()

So, an __initializated__ variable was created to avoid calling __init__() more than once (because no other things are done during the FoBiSConfig class creation), but the first thing we are doing later is manually calling __init__() again.

May I suggest to redesign it?",{},{}
710,IssuesEvent,2018-05-21 10:41:33+00:00,24005390,tBuLi/symfit,2188968,tBuLi,,,opened,Parameters should be allowed as initial values to ODEModel,[],[],0,"In relation to [this SO](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49149241/ode-fitting-with-symfit-for-python-how-to-get-estimations-for-intial-values) question, it might be worth re-investigating how to allow Parameters to be allowed as initial values, e.g.

```python
x0 = Parameter('x0')
ode_model = ODEModel(model_dict, initial={t: 0.0, x: x0, s: 20.0, p: 0.0})
```
A quick scan of the source tells me this should be straightforward, it will require one extra line to dump any Parameters from initial into the list of parameters of the model, and an extra line or two in `__call__` to correctly feed the provided guesses to the ode-solver.",{},{}
712,IssuesEvent,2017-12-14 23:46:29+00:00,24005390,tBuLi/symfit,4319174,egede,,,opened,Likelihood fit returns no covariance matrix,[],[],0,"When I perform a  maximum likelihood fit, there is no covariance matrix returned. See example below

```from symfit import Parameter, Variable, Likelihood, exp
import numpy as np
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define the model for a Gaussian
mu = Parameter(value=1.0)
sigma = Parameter(value=1.0, min=0.5)
x = Variable()
model = (1.0 / sigma) * exp(- (x-mu)*(x-mu) / (2.*sigma*sigma))

# Draw 1000 samples from a Gaussian
nsample=1000
data = np.random.normal(loc=5.0, scale=2.0, size=nsample)

# Do the fitting
fit = Likelihood(model, data)
fit_result = fit.execute(method='L-BFGS-B')
print(fit_result)
print(type(fit_result.params.covariance_matrix))``
```

results in 

```
Parameter Value        Standard Deviation
mu        4.936787e+00 None
sigma     2.000927e+00 None
Fitting status message: CONVERGENCE: NORM_OF_PROJECTED_GRADIENT_<=_PGTOL
Number of iterations:   18
Regression Coefficient: nan

<type 'NoneType'>
```
so minimum is found correctly but there is no covariance matrix. Is this a limitation of `symfit` or a problem with the code above? ",{},{}
716,IssuesEvent,2017-12-09 16:53:19+00:00,57449832,tiran/pysha3,444071,tiran,,,closed,pysha3 uses private 'pystrhex.h' API,[],[],0,According to PyPy upstream (https://bitbucket.org/pypy/pypy/issues/2687/pypy3-is-missing-pystrhexh-breaking-pysha3) pystrhex.h is a private API of CPython and should not be used in the extensions. I would therefore suggest removing the conditional that uses it and always use the local implementation.,{},{}
