6939,IssuesEvent,2016-10-05 23:02:46+00:00,27609645,web2py/pydal,5019985,gi0baro,33118,web2py,closed,Null fields with IS_DATETIME_IN_RANGE is validated,[],[],1,"In my application, I have a field like this:
```
Field('download_date',
          type='datetime',
          required=False,
          notnull=False,
          requires=IS_DATETIME_IN_RANGE(maximum=request.now),
          label=T('Download date')),
```

This field is not required and can have a `null` value. But if my controller try to send data without value for this field (by using db.subscription.validate_and_insert function), I have the following error: `Row {'errors': {'download_date': 'Enter date and time on or before 2016-10-05 12:21:04'}, 'id': None}>`.
After checking the source code of `pydal`, I saw the https://github.com/web2py/pydal/commit/b57adea1f368fb1c9f299121f26cea557f1a5539 commit that change the behavior of the validators by checking all fields of the model instead of only sent fields.

I don't know if it's required to change the behavior of all validators to add a check for null value on each of them or change the call of validators to do not take care of `null` values.",{},{}
6946,IssuesEvent,2017-10-06 03:57:37+00:00,41557383,cloudant/python-cloudant,5661986,illeatmyhat,44642,cloudant,opened,Large bulk uploads using db.bulk_docs() results in a timeout,[],[],0,"Cloudant version 2.6.0
Python version 3.6.2

In the interest of being able to insert and update large datasets because of API call limits, I use db.bulk_docs() to insert a large amount of documents.

If we attempt to use db.bulk_docs() to insert a large amount of data, we get a timeout.
The workaround is to simply insert less documents at a time, though not knowing an exact limitation is rather painful.

```
data = [{""very-large-json-objects"":""almost 2MB combined""}]
db.bulk_docs(data)
```
This will result in `requests.exceptions.ConnectionError: ('Connection aborted.', BrokenPipeError(32, 'Broken pipe'))`


After some stepping, it seems that the POST request is sent using unchunked transfer encoding.
Perhaps consider giving the option to use chunked?",{},{}
