7752,IssuesEvent,2015-06-08 09:05:11+00:00,4421513,mozilla/mozdownload,129603,whimboo,131524,mozilla,closed,Remove support for unsigned candidate builds,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/mozilla/mozdownload/labels/mentored', 'name': 'mentored', 'color': 'bfe5bf'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/mozilla/mozdownload/labels/python', 'name': 'python', 'color': 'c7def8'}]",[],3,"I have been unable to find any unsigned candidate builds. Are we still building these? If not, we should remove this code-path from mozdownload.",{},{}
7754,IssuesEvent,2015-09-15 14:01:37+00:00,4421513,mozilla/mozdownload,129603,whimboo,131524,mozilla,opened,Use a shared HTTP/HTTPS session() for retrieving data,[],[],0,As of now we seem to make individual connections to the remote host for querying every tiny information and finally downloading the build. It would be better to share those connections via a session (http://docs.python-requests.org/en/latest/user/advanced/#session-objects). It can result in a more or less good speed improvement.,{},{}
7774,IssuesEvent,2015-12-29 21:52:06+00:00,527040,recurly/recurly-client-python,185919,bhelx,144605,recurly,closed,Errors unprintable in python 3.5.0 / client 2.2.17,[],[],1,"When I get a traceback from the recurly client, what I see is this:

```
recurly.errors.ValidationError: <unprintable ValidationError object>
```

Digging further, it seems to be caused by a nested exception, thrown in the `__unicode__`/`__str__` methods:

```
 File ""<snip>/lib/python3.5/site-packages/recurly/errors.py"", line 53, in __str__
    return self.__unicode__()
  File ""<snip>/lib/python3.5/site-packages/recurly/errors.py"", line 184, in __unicode__
    return six.u('; ').join(six.text_type(error) for error in self.errors.itervalues())
AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'itervalues'
```

This is probably a python 3.X issue, as `itervalues()` was removed in favor of `values()`. ",{},{}
7775,IssuesEvent,2017-11-15 20:38:55+00:00,527040,recurly/recurly-client-python,2554349,saillsha,144605,recurly,closed,Recurly Transaction call sporadically hangs,[],"[{'login': 'bhelx', 'id': 185919, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/185919?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/bhelx', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/bhelx/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",4,"I have a cron job that does ETL work on recurly data everyday. As part of the script, I call  ```recurly.Transaction.all(sort = 'updated_at', begin_time = YESTERDAY)```

The script occasionally hangs at this point when running in a dev environment using the recurly sandbox key. I'm not sure where in the recurly client it is hanging or what's causing it.",{},{}
