7805,IssuesEvent,2017-10-27 00:01:37+00:00,52136436,sendgrid/python-http-client,146695,thinkingserious,181234,sendgrid,opened,Add a .env_sample file,"[{'id': 674389884, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/sendgrid/python-http-client/labels/difficulty:%20easy', 'name': 'difficulty: easy', 'color': 'f9d0c4', 'default': False}, {'id': 707352402, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/sendgrid/python-http-client/labels/hacktoberfest', 'name': 'hacktoberfest', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}]",[],0,"Our preference is that users have an environment file when using the SendGrid API, because it is less likely that someone would commit their credentials to github.

Please make a couple changes:
- make a .env_sample file that contains: `export SENDGRID_API_KEY=''`
- make (or add) a .gitignore file and include `.env`
- add instructions to the README file about how to copy .env_sample to .env and add the API Key",{},{}
7823,IssuesEvent,2016-09-07 21:15:28+00:00,35100117,neo4j/neo4j-python-driver,12887285,ReedJessen,201120,neo4j,opened,Bolt Driver does not work in Python 3.5,[],[],0,"The following code is sourced from the [ReadMe](neo4j-python-driver/README.rst) page and works in Python 2.7 after installing neo4j-driver.

```python
from neo4j.v1 import GraphDatabase, basic_auth

driver = GraphDatabase.driver(""bolt://hobby-kfkdjimaoibhgbkeccpmfcnl.dbs.graphenedb.com:24786"",
                              auth=basic_auth(""IPStreetSandbox"", ""qF1yZ85Y2nb30STRNLdo""))
session = driver.session()
session.run(""CREATE (a:Person {name:'Bob'})"")
result = session.run(""MATCH (a:Person) RETURN a.name AS name"")
for record in result:
    print(record[""name""])
session.close()
```

When running the same code in Python 3.5 after installing neo4j-driver, I get the following error:
```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""C:/PythonApps/Neo4jBoltDriverTest/run.py"", line 1, in <module>
    from neo4j.v1 import GraphDatabase, basic_auth
  File ""C:\Users\username\AppData\Local\Programs\Python\Python35\lib\site-packages\neo4j\__init__.py"", line 29, in <module>
    from neo4j.core import GraphDatabase, Direction, NotFoundException, BOTH, ANY, INCOMING, OUTGOING
  File ""C:\Users\username\AppData\Local\Programs\Python\Python35\lib\site-packages\neo4j\core.py"", line 19, in <module>
    from _backend import *
ImportError: No module named '_backend'
```

The[ setup.py](neo4j-python-driver/setup.py) file lists up to python 3.4 but not python 3.5 which I expect is reason for this error.  Is this correct?  If so, is there a timeline for when the library will be support python 3.5?",{},{}
7865,IssuesEvent,2016-03-22 22:28:22+00:00,9155431,spotify/annoy,9464836,shawnjhenry,251374,spotify,opened,Strange behavior with extremely large amounts of data.,[],[],0,"Hi,

I'm seeing some curious behavior indexing large amounts of data.  If I index 1 million vectors of size 300 in 32 trees, query time with default settings for top 10 is about 0.005 seconds, so if I want to index 20 million vectors, I can create 20 indices with 1 million vectors each and query in 0.1 seconds (plus a negligible amount of time to sort and filter the total result).  It should be faster to create a single index with 20 million vectors, but when I do that query time skyrockets to 5 seconds.  Any idea why that might be?

Thanks,
Shawn",{},{}
7899,IssuesEvent,2015-04-20 12:46:40+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,1027979,erikbern,251374,spotify,closed,RemoteFileSystem uses wrong path separator,[],[],3,"The RemoteFileSystem uses the client path  separators instead of the remote system path separators.

That means that when trying to write to a Linux RemoteTarget from a Windows Client, the path will be broken (backslashes instead of slashes as path separators, leading to wrong path names).",{},{}
