8152,IssuesEvent,2016-04-26 19:45:04+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,2643092,JordonPhillips,327752,boto,closed,create_load_balancer_listener unnecessarily restrictive,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/boto3/labels/api-question', 'name': 'api-question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],1,"In the documentation for create_load_balancer_listener, it states:

> If the front-end protocol is HTTP, HTTPS, TCP, or SSL, InstanceProtocol must be at the same protocol.

I wonder why this is the case as it is not true for either the Java SDK or aws cli or indeed configuration through Amazon web console.

One of the benefits that AWS state for using the ELB is to allow termination of HTTPS on the ELB and then pass HTTP traffic to the instance, thus unburdening the extra CPU cycles of HTTPS from the instance.

With boto and boto3 it does not allow you to create a listener with HTTPS for the ELB but HTTP for the instance.

Was this a purposeful design choice?  If so, why?

Is there is no reason to the above, I can look at submitting a PR to remove the restriction but I don't want to start work until there is no reason why it's implemented this way.",{},{}
