8811,IssuesEvent,2016-02-02 17:15:40+00:00,1446474,pypa/virtualenv,1110419,pfmoore,647025,pypa,closed,"The new ""download the latest version from the internet"" makes virtualenv creation very slow",[],[],6,"At work, I'm behind a proxy that pip can't use (NTLM). Access to the internet fails, but takes a long time to do so.

As a result, creating a new virtualenv now takes *six minutes* to complete :-( This makes virtualenv essentially unusable, and have to change my automated virtualenv-creation scripts as a result (either to use the built-in venv module, or virtualenv with ```--never-download```).

I can, of course, use ```--never-download```, but remembering to do this is an issue. We did a lot of work when switching to use of wheels for the bundled packages to make creation of virtualenvs fast, particularly on Windows, and this change has lost most of that benefit. I don't have a machine with internet access available at the moment to check, but I know the download process was a source of a lot of slowness when we did the earlier speedup changes.

Can we revert the default to using the bundled packages, maybe with a ```--latest``` option to download the latest versions for people who don't need fast venv creation, need the latest versions and can't (or won't remember to) run ```python -m pip install -U pip setuptools wheel``` after install?",{},{}
8813,IssuesEvent,2017-04-05 14:40:37+00:00,1446474,pypa/virtualenv,33456,markfink,647025,pypa,closed,provide virtualenv version information as environment variable,[],[],3,"We use virtualenv a lot and love it so thank you!

We still have some trouble with old virtualenv versions. I believe the main issue with old versions is that some OS installed packages ""shine"" through. We do not have similar issues with the current ""15.0.1"" version.

What we want to do is to check within a python module which virtualenv version we are using and issue a warning in case an old version is used. I propose an environment variable which is set and exported during "". ./venv/bin/activate"". i.e:

``` text
export VIRTUAL_ENV_VERSION=15.0.2
```

I would like to discuss that with you and also check if you would accept a pull request for that and what the timeline for something like that is to get into a released version.",{},{}
