8998,IssuesEvent,2016-08-10 14:20:10+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,449835,cscheffler,779641,Parsely,opened,Breaking change in latest release – change version number?,[],[],0,"Hi, this isn't really a bug, but more of a versioning thing.

My understanding was that 2.4.1.dev1 should be fully backwards compatible with 2.x.

We just had to change this:
```
kafka_client.cluster.get_offset_manager(consumer_group)
```
to this:
```
kafka_client.cluster.get_group_coordinator(consumer_group)
```
to fix a breaking change in our pykafka upgrade from 2.2.1 to 2.4.1.dev1.

It looks like the change happened from 2.2.1 to 2.3.0.

In 2.2.1: https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/2.2.1/pykafka/cluster.py#L369

In 2.3.0: https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/2.3.0/pykafka/cluster.py#L369

Should an alias perhaps be created for the old method name (perhaps with a deprecation warning), to maintain backwards compatibility?",{},{}
9000,IssuesEvent,2016-03-24 17:44:32+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,723615,emmett9001,779641,Parsely,closed,Kafka consumer partition offset off by 2?,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Parsely/pykafka/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': '0b02e1'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Parsely/pykafka/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],1,"Hi,

I have a kafka topic with a single partition. I would like to create a consumer with the single purpose of returning me the last message that was produced on the channel (and that's it).

The use case is that this is run by the producer at the beginning of each run. The producer listens to some other data source and relays any new entries into the kafka topic. In the case of producer downtime or failures, it needs to recover from where it last left off.

Please let me know if any of the below are not the correct ways to do this. This is basically what I have:

    def getKafkaTopic(topic):
        client = KafkaClient(zookeeper_hosts=getZookeeperHosts())
        return client.topics[topic]

and then

    topic = getKafkaTopic('some.topic.name')
    consumer = topic.get_simple_consumer(consumer_group=""some_consumer_group"")
    partitions = [p for p in consumer.partitions.itervalues()]
    offset_pairs = [(p, p.latest_available_offset() - 2) for p in partitions]
    consumer.reset_offsets(partition_offsets=offset_pairs)

This works. However, I'm baffled at the requirement for `p.latest_available_offset() - 2`.

Given that an offset value in kafka points to the ""next message to be consumed"", I would expect a consumer at `p.latest_available_offset()` to block until the next message is produced, so that would be as expected. However, `p.latest_available_offset() - 1` will also block until the next message is produced, whereas `p.latest_available_offset() - 2` will get me the last message produced.

Is this an off by one error somewhere in pykafka? Or am I just not understanding kafka?

Thanks,
Jack

**PyKafka version**: 2.2.0
**Kafka version**: 0.8.2
",{},{}
