12716,IssuesEvent,2015-01-10 11:24:22+00:00,14318232,soft-matter/pims,8937919,caspervdw,5857177,soft-matter,closed,Display 3D stacks,[],[],2,"Hi,

I've found this nice HTML/JS display tool for z-stacks: http://codepen.io/will-moore/pen/Beuyc
It would be great if this functionality would be added to pims for standard display of 3D image stacks.

Below I've made a simple version, this first saves images to a subfolder of the iPython notebook server and then builds the script that refers to this same folder. This is not very neat but the best I can do.. Does somebody have any better ideas?

```
def gen3DIpythonObject(self):
        from PIL import Image
        from os.path import join
        from IPython.display import HTML, Javascript, display
        from random import random #to force browser refresh of images
        
        savepath = '<my documents folder>\IPython Notebooks\zstacks'
         #can you get this path from ipython package somewhere?
        
        d = self.shape[0]
        w = min(512,self.shape[2])
        h = self.shape[1] * w // self.shape[2]
        x = (self - self.min()) / (self.max() - self.min())
        
        for n in xrange(self.shape[0]):
            img = Image.fromarray((x[n] * 256).astype('uint8')).resize((w,h))
            img.save(join(savepath,'image'+str(n)+'.png'), format='png')
            
            
        # The piece of HTML/JS was adapted from http://codepen.io/will-moore/pen/Beuyc    
        mainimg = ''
        for n in xrange(d):
            mainimg = mainimg + '<img src=""zstacks/image'+str(n)+'.png?' + str(random()) + '"" class=""large_image""/>'
        
        html = """"""<div id=""large_img_container"">
            """""" + mainimg + """"""    
        </div>
        <p id=""indicator"">0</p>
        """"""
        
        css = """"""<style media=""screen"" type=""text/css"">
        body {
            font-family: arial;
        }
        
        #large_img_container {
            position:relative;
            float: left;
            width:"""""" + str(w) + """"""px;
            height:"""""" + str(h) + """"""px;
            overflow:hidden;
            Cache-Control: no-store
        }
        
        .large_image {
            position:absolute;
            top:0px; left:0px;
            display: none;
        }
        </style>
        """"""
        
        js = """"""
        (function($){
            $(function() {
        
            var SRC_ROOT = ""zstacks/"",
                SIZE_X = """""" + str(w) + """""",
                SIZE_Y = """""" + str(h) + """""",
                SIZE_Z = """""" + str(d) + """""",
                large_image_styles = [],
                z_index = 0;
                
            $("".large_image"").each(function() {
                large_image_styles.push(this.style);
            });
            
            // show the specified plane in the main viewer
            var show_plane = function(theZ) {
                if (theZ < 0 || theZ >= SIZE_Z) return;
                z_index = theZ
                // hide all planes...
                for (var i=0; i<large_image_styles.length; i++){
                    large_image_styles[i].display = 'none';
                }
                large_image_styles[z_index].display = 'block';
                $(""#indicator"").text(z_index);
            }
            
            var onMouseWheel = function(e) {
                e = e.originalEvent;
                var incr = e.wheelDelta>0||e.detail<0?1:-1;
                show_plane(z_index + incr);
                return false;
            }
            
            $(""#large_img_container"").bind(""mousewheel DOMMouseScroll"", onMouseWheel);
        
            // finally, start by showing the first plane
            show_plane("""""" + str(d//2) + """""");
        });
        })(jQuery);
        """"""
        return display(HTML(css + html),Javascript(js))
```",{},{}
12717,IssuesEvent,2015-12-08 20:55:52+00:00,14318232,soft-matter/pims,2985325,nkeim,5857177,soft-matter,closed,ENH: Slicing-aware reader methods,[],[],13,"This is an architectural issue at the intersection of #147, #153, and #158.

### The problem

Currently, pims `SliceableIterable` objects wisely forward unknown method calls to their ancestors, which allows methods to be ""inherited"" from the reader object that opened the file. However, those methods could take frame numbers as their arguments. For example, the Cine and (unmerged) NorpixSeq classes have methods for reading the timestamp of frame *i*. Being able to retrieve a timestamp without reading the entire image can make a large performance difference in some applications. In a similar fashion, these proprietary formats can store other (as yet unsupported) information such as voltages or event markers.

Therefore, methods like `get_time(frameno)` should be aware that they are being called via a child.

### A solution
`FramesSequence`-derived objects that want to support this feature provide the context `_use_map`, which would be used within the child `SliceableIterable` as follows (oversimplified for clarity):

```
# Call get_time() on the parent object
with self._ancestor.use_map(self.indices):
    self._ancestor.get_time(*args, **kw)
```

The reader class would then implement `get_time` as:

```
def get_time(self, frameno):
   actual_frameno = self._indexmap(frameno)
   # Return time of actual_frameno...
```

`use_map()`, `_indexmap()`, etc. would be implemented in the `FramesSequence` base class. `use_map()` could be thread-safe.

Thoughts? I'm open to more elegant solutions, or to the possibility that this is too much of a niche feature!",{},{}
