12875,IssuesEvent,2016-01-22 00:41:16+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1360539,bacongobbler,6117407,deis,closed,Proxying some apps through mashape/kong API gateway,[],[],3,"I would like to use https://github.com/Mashape/kong to proxy some of my deis apps. Kong is an ""Open-source, Microservice & API Management Layer"" that does a few things like rate limiting and authentication.

My understanding is that I could deploy kong as a regular deis app and add my proxied apps using the kong api (going from the docs, haven't tested yet):

```bash
$ curl -i -X POST \
  --url http://kong.deis.domain.com/apis/ \
  --data 'name=api1' \
  --data 'upstream_url=http://api1.deis.domain.com/' \
  --data 'request_host=api1.domain.com'
```

and then just add `api1.domain.com` to my kong app to make sure it receives requests to this host:

```bash
deis domains:add api1.domain.com --app=kong
```

Everything looks good so far. Now, how would I make `api1.deis.domain.com` unreachable from outside my cluster? (I'm on AWS). It seems one approach would be to use [IP whitelisting](http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/security_considerations/#ip-whitelist) but then I would have to declare each app that needs to be public manually (`deis config:set -a some-public-app DEIS_WHITELIST=""0.0.0.0/0""`). Is that correct? Other recommended approaches?

",{},{}
12878,IssuesEvent,2016-01-21 20:21:28+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1360539,bacongobbler,6117407,deis,closed,feat(router) Allow router page customization,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/router', 'name': 'router', 'color': 'bfdadc'}]",[],16,"Right now deis returns the default nginx error page.
Maybe this could be an alternative to provide a default (with a deis styled output) to indicate that an error occurred and also to return a message in a format that the client is expecting (if the accept header is application/json I don't expect html as result)

this is the last version that I'm running.

```
    # Map response error type watching header Content-Type
    map $http_content_type $customType {
        default                 html;
        ~application/json json;
    }

    server {
        listen 80 default_server;

        # Inside /app/errors create files with name 404.html and 404.json (and the rest)
        # the content of 404.json could be:
        # { ""message"" : ""404 Not Found"" }
        # By default the content of index returns the same content that 404.
        root /app/errors;

        error_page 403 404 502 503 504  /$status.$customType;

        # Remove etags
        etag                            off;
    }
```

I'm expecting #1754 so I can provide a PR that will allow to the end user to customize the look and feel of the pages uploading a zip file to the store.

Just as reference this is the full template https://github.com/aledbf/deis/blob/custom_router/router/templates/nginx.conf",{},{}
12887,IssuesEvent,2017-07-03 17:43:54+00:00,53438969,globus/globus-cli,1300022,sirosen,6120321,globus,closed,Recursive dir listing has potentially dangerous implications service-side -- limit it or remove it,"[{'id': 370346004, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/globus/globus-cli/labels/blocked:%20design', 'name': 'blocked: design', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}, {'id': 455897091, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/globus/globus-cli/labels/internals', 'name': 'internals', 'color': 'c2e0c6', 'default': False}, {'id': 455896809, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/globus/globus-cli/labels/usability', 'name': 'usability', 'color': 'd93f0b', 'default': False}]",[],1,"The case we're concerned about is the pathological case of hundreds of nested directories expanding to huge numbers of files (m/billions).
Per notes from Karl, we'd need to switch traversal to be breadth-first and unbuffered output to handle that case at all -- makes perfect sense, though unbuffered JSON output will require careful handling and some testing to ensure that the results are valid JSON.

To resolve, we have three paths forward (there may be more?):
- Remove recursive `ls` from the CLI
- Add it to the SDK and limit the total number of dirs to `ls` to some ""small"" but reasonable number -- e.x. 50
- Add it to the SDK and enforce an N second sleep every M dirs, where N and M are both small (guessing 1s every 25 dirs)

This is only worth discussing as an SDK addition (and not purely as a CLI feature) because we've made it very easy to build your own version of recursive `ls`.
Unless we make it easier to use the ""correct"" version than to build your own, we haven't actually solved the problem.

Removing it from the CLI is viable but may be worse than adding a `recursive=True` option to the SDK `ls` -- I just don't trust that people won't go building this themselves. It therefore seems a poor way of protecting the service.

Given the choice between a hard limit and a sleep, the sleep has much better semantics.
It doesn't mess with error modes at all -- an SDKLimitExceeded error will be confusing to people, and is likely to break scripts unexpectedly as their inputs scale up.
The sleep behavior also sets the tone correctly for a future universe in which that kind of rate limiting is enforced service side in addition to being done client-side.

There's already been some discussion of these, but I'm moving it into issues to better track status and decisions.
I'd appreciate input from @karlito-go and @ranantha on this one.
",{},{}
12921,IssuesEvent,2015-09-19 14:23:30+00:00,5196969,chardet/chardet,976345,dan-blanchard,6211498,chardet,opened,Should support giving a list of encodings to restrict predictions,[],[],0,"Since people sometimes know what the possible encodings they may receive may be, it would be nice if we supported filtering the set of predictions to only include those.  It might help alleviate some inaccuracies with short strings.",{},{}
