13065,IssuesEvent,2017-09-30 11:04:20+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,293525,ijstokes,6392739,conda,opened,Create conda service to support multiuser operations,[],[],0,"conda in a multiuser environment continues to be problematic.

My best (high-level) idea for how to address this is is to have conda in a multi-user setting implemented not as a pure file system-based transactional service but rather as a persistent API-based service where users authenticate to the service, make a request for a conda operation from the conda daemon service, and that daemon service then performs the operations according to some policy but all (in memory and on disk) as a particular account.  Permissions for any given user to perform any particular conda operation becomes part of some conda-specific security policy and access to conda-installed software becomes a matter of IT configuration of POSIX users and groups.  At that stage if there are any nuances with POSIX.1e ACLs it can be added as a stage in the ""conda service"" to fix ACLs after any write operations -- if necessary.

Doing this would involve creating a conda server and a conda client, with the server wrapping the vanilla (single-user) file-system based conda.",{},{}
13075,IssuesEvent,2017-05-12 21:41:06+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,Don't fail conda install when Windows menu items fail to install,"[{'id': 413890457, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/source:cio', 'name': 'source:cio', 'color': 'c2e0c6', 'default': False}, {'id': 16544530, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/type:bug', 'name': 'type:bug', 'color': 'b60205', 'default': False}]",[],1,"In the case when a user is installing conda packages on Windows and the packages attempt to create Window menu items but the user does not have sufficient privileges to create the item, do not fail the install but instead only fail to install the menu items.

Currently when menu item creation fails due to insufficient privileges the entire conda package install will fail.  This is often not necessary or desirable.  A warning is sufficient.  By continuing the install instead of failing to install the packages the user can still install and use the packages from notebooks and the command line even if the menu items are not present.

A good example, create a new environment with ipython in it.  The user will be prompted for credentials to create the menu items, press Cancel and the entire env creation will fail.  It would be better to create the env without the menu items.
",{},{}
