14880,IssuesEvent,2017-12-06 22:08:18+00:00,26876372,dateutil/dateutil,1377457,pganssle,9849410,dateutil,closed,Switch builds over to using tox,"[{'id': 193509772, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/build', 'name': 'build', 'color': 'bfdadc', 'default': False}, {'id': 149492527, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 149492528, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/help%20wanted', 'name': 'help wanted', 'color': '159818', 'default': True}, {'id': 667039516, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/low-difficulty', 'name': 'low-difficulty', 'color': '0e8a16', 'default': False}]",[],2,"The way I've got the builds in travis and appveyor set up is messing with the coverage metrics (see #528).

Given that we're already maintaining a `tox.ini` (which is not actually automatically tested, mind you!), it's probably a good idea to switch over the builds to use `tox`.

Rather than just have a single build that runs `tox`, it's probably best to use `tox -e <environment>` in the `script`. Once we're using tox, we can also add a `changedir` directive in the tox environments so that the tests are run against the installed version.",{},{}
