16761,IssuesEvent,2018-02-09 21:43:59+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,16142208,jwhui,16142269,openthread,closed,[code-style] change from astyle to clang-format,"[{'id': 397568980, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/P4', 'name': 'P4', 'color': 'AFDF00', 'default': False}, {'id': 355043113, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}]",[],1,"The OpenThread project currently uses [astyle](http://astyle.sourceforge.net/) to automatically format code and enforce the [OpenThread style guide](https://github.com/openthread/openthread/blob/master/STYLE_GUIDE.md).  In general, I've found astyle to be fairly limited.

This is a proposal to change to [clang-format 5](http://releases.llvm.org/5.0.0/tools/clang/docs/ClangFormat.html), which provides a number of useful [options](http://releases.llvm.org/5.0.0/tools/clang/docs/ClangFormatStyleOptions.html) not supported by astyle.

Some examples:
- Reordering include statements.
- Reformatting constructor initializers.
- Aligned assignments.
- Aligned declarations.
- Aligned end-of-line comments.
- Adding/fixing end-of-namespace comments.

Review the diff in #2534.

This issue supersedes #1466.",{},{}
16772,IssuesEvent,2016-10-28 15:48:05+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,16142208,jwhui,16142269,openthread,closed,Implement MPL delayed retransmissions.,"[{'id': 355043113, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 397568778, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/P2', 'name': 'P2', 'color': 'DF8F00', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'LuDuda', 'id': 5144764, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/5144764?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/LuDuda', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/LuDuda/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",6,The current MPL implementation retransmits MPL messages only once and without delay.  The implementation needs to be enhanced such that a router retransmits each MPL message multiple times with a randomized delay.,{},{}
16775,IssuesEvent,2017-02-22 17:16:02+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,16142208,jwhui,16142269,openthread,closed,Packet dropped due to kThreadError_NoBufs when address is not in the Cache,"[{'id': 355043111, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ee0701', 'default': True}, {'id': 397568778, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/openthread/openthread/labels/P2', 'name': 'P2', 'color': 'DF8F00', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'jwhui', 'id': 16142208, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/16142208?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/jwhui', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jwhui/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",2,"During testing on Windows I've hit a weird problem with ping. I was wondering if that's my wrong understanding or if there's a bug. Could you please help me with this?
I've created a network with 27 devices (15 of them - children, other - routers).
Then I tried to ping each router from every other. Leader 0 succeeded in doing so with all routers except for the last one - 26. 
Router 26th addresses were:
```
fdde:ad00:beef:0:0:ff:fe00:4000
fdde:ad00:beef:0:6eaf:cef3:6f01:b682
fe80:0:0:0:e846:33cc:e6e1:862            (wasn't used for ping)
```
When I tried to ping the first one, I did get a response. But second one never responded.
When I tried to debug the driver, I went through the following steps:
In `ThreadError Ip6::HandleDatagram` first it determined that packet is to be forwarded:
```
}
    else                        <<<==== This means unicast, which it is
    {
        if (IsUnicastAddress(header.GetDestination()))
        {
            receive = true;
        }
        else if (!header.GetDestination().IsLinkLocal())
        {
            forward = true;   <<<===== HERE set to be forwarded
        }
```
In here it proceeded to forward the message:
```
else
{
      hopLimit = header.GetHopLimit();
      message.Write(Header::GetHopLimitOffset(), Header::GetHopLimitSize(), &hopLimit);
      SuccessOrExit(error = ForwardMessage(message, messageInfo, nextHeader));           <<=== HERE
}

```
Then `Ip6::ForwardMessage` > `ThreadNetif::SendMessage` > `MeshForwarder::SendMessage` it set the message for direct transmission and enqueued it:
```
else
        {
            // not destined for a sleepy child
            aMessage.SetDirectTransmission();
        }
...
SuccessOrExit(error = mSendQueue.Enqueue(aMessage));
```
So far everything is good.
Afterwards, in `MeshForwarder::GetDirectTransmission()` the message is retrieved:
```
switch (curMessage->GetType())
        {
        case Message::kTypeIp6:
            error = UpdateIp6Route(*curMessage);            <<==== This is being called
            break;
```
In `MeshForwarder::UpdateIp6Route`:
```
else if ((neighbor = mNetif.GetMle().GetNeighbor(ip6Header.GetDestination())) != NULL)
            {
                mMeshDest = neighbor->mValid.mRloc16;
            }
            else if (mNetif.GetNetworkDataLeader().IsOnMesh(ip6Header.GetDestination()))
            {
                SuccessOrExit(error = mNetif.GetAddressResolver().Resolve(ip6Header.GetDestination(), mMeshDest));                          <<<<===== This one is being called
            }
```
And finally in `AddressResolver::Resolve` it fails to find address in the mCache:
```
ThreadError error = kThreadError_None;
    Cache *entry = NULL;

    for (int i = 0; i < kCacheEntries; i++)
    {
        if (mCache[i].mState != Cache::kStateInvalid)
        {
            if (memcmp(&mCache[i].mTarget, &aEid, sizeof(mCache[i].mTarget)) == 0)
            {
                entry = &mCache[i];
                break;
            }
        }
        else if (entry == NULL)
        {
            entry = &mCache[i];
        }
    }

    VerifyOrExit(entry != NULL, error = kThreadError_NoBufs);              <<== HERE it returns the error
```
Going back to the `MeshForwarder::GetDirectTransmission()` the packet is being dropped due to the previous error:
```
switch (error)
        {
        case kThreadError_None:
            ExitNow();

        case kThreadError_AddressQuery:
            mSendQueue.Dequeue(*curMessage);
            mResolvingQueue.Enqueue(*curMessage);
            continue;

        case kThreadError_Drop:
        case kThreadError_NoBufs:                 <<<=== Here it's being dequeued and disposed of
            mSendQueue.Dequeue(*curMessage);
            curMessage->Free();
            continue;
```
My understanding of the sources and documentation is that after failing to find a record in the queue, node should have queried the address (and that's logical). So, `kThreadError_AddressQuery` should have been returned instead of `kThreadError_NoBufs`, and the packet should have been enqueued for Address Resolving, shouldn't it?",{},{}
