17205,IssuesEvent,2016-03-28 06:43:08+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,885054,wolfv,17565521,pybind,opened,Binding different types with the same name leads to segfaults,[],[],0,"I accidentally used the same name twice which lead to hard-to-debug segfaults that only happened when the class got imported twice or some other python module was loaded. 

Therefore I think it might be nice to do a compile-time or runtime check if the name was already registered.

However, adding

```
        for (auto other_info : internals.registered_types_py) {
            std::string other = ((const detail::type_info *) (other_info.second))->type->tp_name;
            if (strcmp(other.c_str(), full_name.c_str())) {
                pybind11_fail(full_name + "" registered previously!"");
            }
        }
```
to the `initialize (type_record *rec)` code didn't work because the types are apparently registered more than once if they are imported from different python scripts.

I am happy to make a pull request if I get a hint to where/how to put the check :)",{},{}
17210,IssuesEvent,2017-01-05 11:56:10+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,5435649,myd7349,17565521,pybind,opened,Usage of `PYBIND11_OVERLOAD*` is misleading,[],[],0,"In [docs/advanced/classes.rst], there is an example code snippet looks like this:
```cpp
    class PyAnimal : public Animal {
    public:
        using Animal::Animal; // Inherit constructors
        std::string go(int n_times) override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD_PURE(std::string, Animal, go, n_times); }
        std::string name() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(std::string, Animal, name, ); }
    };
