17445,IssuesEvent,2017-06-14 10:06:34+00:00,56847043,nfcpy/nfcpy,6604011,nehpetsde,18479744,nfcpy,closed,PN532 Polling slows down as inactive time increases,[],[],5,"I am writing an application which runs on a Raspberry Pi 3 (Jessie) with a PN532 on UART. The application polls continuously for a tag with the following settings:

rdwr_options = {
    'targets': ['106B'],
    'on-connect': lambda tag: False,
	'iterations': 1,
	'interval': 1
}

tag = clf.connect(rdwr=rdwr_options)

The application runs in a loop where the ContactlessFrontend will attempt to connect again after a tag is scanned. All is fine when tags are being scanned actively (short intervals of a few minutes at most). The problem occurs when a tag is not scanned after an hour or so, and the issue gets worst in relation to the inactive time.

After an hour or so, it takes about 5 seconds to scan a tag. After 24 hours, it takes about ~20 seconds to scan a tag, and ~10s on the subsequent scan. The time it takes to scan gets reduced as more scans are connected and will eventually work as intended in the settings. (After about 5-6 scans it will scan in the interval and iterations of 1 as inputted in the settings).

Thanks!",{},{}
17452,IssuesEvent,2017-10-12 19:04:00+00:00,58776721,googledatalab/pydatalab,6488462,foxwendy,18582876,googledatalab,opened,Extract query result with non-table output_option is not async at all,[],[],0,"I wanted to extract a large set of result from my query to CSV file, so that I can easily download from GCS and load it into dataframe for further processing. I usually run this process for a list of queries. So I'd prefer to fire async jobs. The async mode worked perfectly fine if I just need to result into bigquery tables. But seems doesn't work for other output options (such as GCS file or local file or dataframe). I dived into the source code, and trace to the code piece shown in the following screenshot. `extract_job.result()` seems to turn async mode into sync mode already. As a result, even I used `query.execute_async(output_options=bq.QueryOutput.file(_file_name,use_cache=use_cache),context = _context)`, it's not executing asynchronously. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6488462/31513863-9fcb5486-af5d-11e7-8596-4174fa44b27e.png)
",{},{}
17454,IssuesEvent,2017-04-14 00:46:05+00:00,58776721,googledatalab/pydatalab,1424661,yebrahim,18582876,googledatalab,closed,Storage delete operations are not sync,[],[],2,"As pointed out by @craigcitro, `Object.delete` and `Bucket.delete` actually submit delete jobs to the storage service, so they're not exactly synchronous operations, which is different from user expectations.

