ts_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, {'login': 'jma7', 'id': 22623882, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/22623882?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/jma7', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jma7/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"Given that it is relatively troublesome to set up and use task queues, we should design a new ""cluster"" queue to facilitate the use of traditional clusters with PBS/Torch/SunGrid. The following is a short description of the features that will need to be fully developed and implemented.

1. **`task` statement**: the task directive will be responsible for sending jobs to task queues and clusters. It is chosen because we have a mechanism already to send necessary environmental information to the tasks and make them self-contained jobs. The task statement should define

2.  **job parameters** such as memory, node, walltime etc should be acceptable by `task` statement. (issue #240)

3. **how to transfer files** this is related to #257 . Basically if the cluster and desktop are on different filesystems, we will need a way to automatically transfer input files to cluster and transfer output files back. Interface wise we can
    
    * define global file transfer command. e.g.
        `sos config --set to_cluster 'rsync -av {} mycluster:/path/project/`
        `sos config --set from_cluster `rsync -av mycluster:/path/project/{} {}'

    * automatic file transfer. SoS will transfer all input files automatically to the cluster before execution, and transfer all output files back after execution.

    * explicit file transfer: users can specify files and directories to be transferred.

4. **how to submit jobs** Not sure how to do this, but the easiest method seems to be defining a command to remotely submit a jobs (e.g. `ssh mycluster:...`). The key part is that we should get a handle of ""job"" (job id) for query purpose.

4. **how to monitor jobs** Not sure how to do this but we could potentially query the status with job id using commands. Note that there can be separate web or command line monitoring interface for clusters.

5. **how to wait for the completion of jobs in batch mode** The step will simply wait for the completion of the job (signature written).

6. **how to wait for the completion of jobs in Jupyter notebook**. The front-end can collect the jobs that are running and display widgets to indicate status of the jobs.

7. **prevention of duplicated jobs**. Each job will has a remote signature and a lock so duplicated jobs will be prevented (the same job id would be returned.

8. **A sos daemon**? It might worth the trouble to run a sos daemon to accept, submit and monitor jobs.

We should first investigate other technologies such as [ganglia](http://ganglia.info/), snakemake,  [drmaa-python](http://drmaa-python.github.io/), and [pbs-drmaa](http://apps.man.poznan.pl/trac/pbs-drmaa).",{},{}
17686,IssuesEvent,2017-03-13 02:44:29+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SOS,9889312,BoPeng,20074389,vatlab,opened,Too much status update.,"[{'id': 325435539, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SOS/labels/request', 'name': 'request', 'color': '159818', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'BoPeng', 'id': 9889312, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/9889312?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/BoPeng', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/BoPeng/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"Currently the task manager sends status update for all tasks to the frontend. Ideally, it should be enough to send only the changed status but before of the async nature of frontend display, it is possible that some tasks are not displayed when the status is updated, so their status will not be updated at all. 

Right now I do not see an obvious side effect of sending so much status update, but it can be problem when the system has a lot of tasks. Remember that the task engine checks the status of ALL tasks, not only the one that is updated.",{},{}
17688,IssuesEvent,2017-05-22 17:52:16+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SOS,9889312,BoPeng,20074389,vatlab,opened,%render --hide-input?,"[{'id': 325435541, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SOS/labels/discussion', 'name': 'discussion', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': False}, {'id': 325435539, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SOS/labels/request', 'name': 'request', 'color': '159818', 'default': False}]",[],0,"The new [%render](http://vatlab.github.io/SOS/doc/documentation/Notebook_Interface.html#%render-148)  magic is the closest thing we can do to R's inline expression (#390). It is currently limited in that it can only handle SoS output but it can be more powerful than R's inline expression because we can generate document programatically.

I am wondering if we should also add an option `--hide-input` for this magic so that it will render the output and hide the input at the same time. Some frontend magic would be needed to make the cell behave like a markdown cell.",{},{}
17699,IssuesEvent,2018-02-05 05:36:45+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SoS,917985,gaow,20074389,vatlab,opened,Cannot use `concurrent` for multiple statement in non-task mode,[],[],0,"Here is a MWE:

```
[1]
input: [f'{x+1}.txt' for x in range(2)], group_by = 1, concurrent = True
bash: expand = True
 echo {_input}
python: expand = True
 print({_input:r})
```

Running this script I get a warning: 

```
WARNING: Input groups are executed sequentially because of existence of directives between statements.
```

and the jobs are not done in parallel. However it seems to me that there should not be any ambiguous logic here that prevents the parallelism. So am I missing something here? What can I do to still achieve `concurrent` without using `task`?",{},{}
